MissionCommands.Message: Apollo 13, Houston.
Go ahead, Joe.
Okay. We have a PTC REFSMMAT ready, if you're ready to go P00 and Accept, we'll stick it in there.
Okay. Stand by.
Okay. I'm P00 and Accept, Joe.
Okay. Roger that.
Apollo 13, Houston. The computer is yours. Over.
Okay. Going to Block.
Roger.
Okay, it is time to align the IMU with the PTC REFSMMAT that was uplinked.
On the DSKY, Key V37E N52E.
Okay, program 52.
Key V22E +1E to input option 1.
Then hit PRO to start the preferred IMU alignment.
Okay, Houston. Do you copy 13's torqueing angles on the P52?
13, Houston. Leave them up just a second, and we'll get them down.
13, Houston. Okay. We got 'em. [Press PRO to torque the gyros]
Okay. The time of torqueing was {MET} .
Roger. We copy.
Hello, Houston; Apollo 13.
13, Houston. Go ahead.
Okay. I just got all hooked up to get in my comm system here, and I just wanted to check out. I've got my suit stowed, a few other odds and ends done, and I'm back in business again.
Okay. Good deal. We're kind of hanging loose down here. I've got a Lift-off plus 15 PAD. There's no hurry to read it up, so let us know when you're ready.
Okay.
Okay, Houston. Go ahead with the PAD.
Okay, Jim. Lift-off plus 15 PAD. GETI, 015:00. Delta-VT, 5622. longitude, minus 165, and GET 400K, 047:04. Over.
Okay, Houston. Lift-off plus 15: GETI, 015:00; 5622; minus 165; 047:04. Is that correct?
That's right, Jim.
Ok, according to the flight plan, we have a GDC ALIGN.
[Complete GDC align, press DONE when complete. You can follow the G&C GENERAL > GDC ALIGN TO IMU full or simplified approach].
Ok, GDC align complete.
<<P23 - CISLUNAR NAVIGATION procedure, not yet implemented>>
And, Joe, we confirmed there's no midcourse-1. Over.
That is affirmative as far as I know. Let's get a final check on it, Jim.
Okay. Because we're standing by. We want to do a fuel cell purge and a waste water dump.
Okay, Jim. We confirm that there will be no midcourse-1.
Okay. Sounds good.
Okay. Houston, 13.
13, Houston. Go ahead.
Hey, Joe. Do you want to dump waste water down to 25 percent. Is that right?
That's affirm. [RUN the COMMAND MODULE -> SYSTEMS: ECS > WASTE WATER TANK DRAIN checklist]
Okay, in work.
Okay. [Complete the checklist, reduce water to 25%]
Then it's the fuel cells O2 purge. [RUN the COMMAND MODULE -> SYSTEMS: EPS > FC PURGE checklist]
Hey, Joe, we're also purging fuel cells O2 now.
Okay, Jack. [Complete the O2 Purge on FC1, FC2 and FC3, then CLEAR the checklist, skipping the H2 purge section]
Okay, Houston. The fuel cell purge and waste water dump are complete.
Roger, Apollo 13. And this is your relief CapCom shift on now.
Well, good evening, Vance.
Boy, you sure made it back fast.
Yes. You guys had a beautiful launch, there. Really nice.
Could you follow it all the way up, Vance?
No, I didn't see staging. It was too hazy for that, but we could see it for a few miles anyway.
I'll tell you, it's sure an interesting ride.
Right.
Ok, let us maneuver to the PTC attitude.
Set CMC Mode to AUTO.
[Key V49E, then use V25E to enter 0, 110, 0, then start the maneuver. Press DONE when started.]
Ok, maneuvering to PTC attitude.
Houston, Apollo 13.
Rog. Go ahead, Jim.

Roger. We're at that stage now where we're going to take some Earth weather photography. If you're standing by, I have the camera aimed at the Earth right now, and I'll give you a mark when I take the first picture.
Roger. We copy, Jim. We'll be standing by for the mark.
[Optional: Look out the hatch or forward window and be prepared to press the Screenshot key on MARK. Press READY when you are ready to take the screenshot]
Okay, Houston. 3, 2, 1, MARK.
Roger, copy.

[In the real Apollo 13 mission they took 11 pictures of Earth, one every ~20 minutes when it rolled past the view during PTC roll until about 11 hours into the mission. Feel free to grab a shot whenever you see Earth passing or through external view.]
And Apollo 13, Houston. Over.
Go ahead.
For the PTC, recommend that you disable quads A and B. Over.
Okay. Disable quads A and B, will do; and soon as Jack gets finished thrashing around, we'll be going to that PTC mode.
Okay.
Ok, I'm ready for the PTC roll.
Okay, Houston. We're starting PTC. We're disabling quads A and B now.
Roger, Apollo 13. Houston copies.
[Then start the PTC roll maneuver. RUN the COMMAND MODULE -> G&C GENERAL > (V79) Orbrate/PTC checklist]
[Default values are OK, rate of 0.3 degrees and deadband of 30 degrees. Complete the checklist.]
Ok, PTC roll is running.
All quads are disabled and we should be in a PTC roll.
Roger.
Hello, Houston. This is 13. How do you read?
13, Houston's reading loud and clear. How do you read?
Okay. And do you have any estimate, Vance, on how long we'll be charging battery B?
Stand by 1, Fred.
Apollo 13, Houston.
Go ahead.
We'll be charging for 4 to 5 hours yet, Jim.
Roger.
Okay, let us change the LiOH canister. [Change the A CO2 filter. Press DONE when complete]
It is time to deactivate the primary evaporator.
[Hold INCR up for 58 seconds. Press DONE when complete.]
Primary evaporator deactivated.
Apollo 13, Houston. We have a CSM state vector to send you. Request P00 and Accept at your convenience.
Okay, Vance. There's P00 and Accept.
Okay, it's coming up.
13, the computer's yours again.
Okay, going back to Block.
Rog.
Earth starting to look pretty small there?
Well, looking at here, Vance, it's hard to be convinced it's even the Earth. All we see is water and clouds.
Okay, let us do another IMU REALIGN. [Complete a P52, option 3 (REFSMMAT). You can optionally use the G&N ALIGNMENTS > P52 AID: REFSMMAT checklist. Press DONE when complete.]
Hey, you still there, Vance?
Rog. Go ahead.

I guess the world really does turn. I can see some of my landmasses now. It must be Australia down near the bottom and I guess we haven't really figured out what's over the - to the left. It must be some part of Asia. China, probably.
Hey, maybe the fact that you verified that the Earth really turns, we can call this Haise's Theory, huh?
Very good, Vance. Very good.
It's looking good for you, Vance.
No, seriously. Very interesting, we can see on the map now that you're between Guam and Hawaii and a little bit north, and you're almost out 60,000 miles.

Vance, to our calculations, we have taken about 10 Earth window photography pictures. I see nothing coming up here except to close the waste stowage vent here in a little while. I was thinking about getting squared away to bed down for the evening pretty soon.
Okay. That sounds good, Jim. FAO here would like to request just one more picture before you bed down, if you don't mind.
Okay. We'll come through with one more picture.
Okay.
Apollo 13, Houston.
Go ahead, Houston.

A couple of items, Jim. The first is, the time for closing the waste stowage vent is 12:24. If you turn in before that time, why it's, it's okay as far as we're concerned down here to close it before that time, just before you go to bed.
Roger.
[You can optionally take the last screenshot of Earth the next time it comes into view, this concludes the picture taking]
Houston, 13.
Roger. Go ahead.
We're starting our presleep checklist and no medication.
Okay. The Doc says very good.
And, Houston, is there any onboard readouts that you don't have from us.
Stand by 1. We need the LM/CM Delta-P for one thing, and I'll check back in a minute with the others.
Okay. And we still have the vent valve open. We'll close it one of the last things.
Roger.
13, Houston.
Go ahead.
Only other readouts we need are those on page 3-13 of the Flight Plan. Bat C, Pyro Bat A, Pyro Bat B, RCS A, B, C, and D readings, and DC Indicator select Main A or B.
Okay. Stand by.
And, Vance, we're still charging Bat B. Did you want to dispense with that in a few minutes?
Stand by on that, Fred.
[Note down the Bat C, Pyro Bat A, Pyro Bat B voltages, and the RCS A, B, C, and D readings, and set the DC Indicator select Main A or B. Press DONE when complete.]
Roger. Copy that.

Okay. In answer to the battery-charging question, I calculate it should be fully charged at 12:35. Play that one, though, the same as the waste vent. If you want to do it earlier because you're turning in, why that's fine with us.
Okay, we'll continue on with a few other things we got to get done, and just before turning in, we'll check with you, and you can remind us then.
Okay
Okay, Vance. Requesting clearance now to turn the vent valve back to Close again, and also the battery charge, Off.
Roger. That's fine with us, Jim. Proceed.
Vent it for 5 seconds.
Close the battery vent.
Check that the System Test 7A reads less than 1.5 vdc.
Check that system test 5B (battery relay voltage) shows > 3 vdc
Ok, then the pre-sleep checklist. Cycle cryo fans.
Cryo fans cycled.
Waste Mngmt Ovdb Drain is OFF.
Waste Stow Vent is OFF.
Emer Cabin Press is Both.
Surge Tank O2 valve is ON.
Repress Pkg O2 is OFF.
Cabin Pressure relief RH is Norm
Cabin Pressure relief LH is Norm
[Close the LM hatch]
Pressure Eq valve to CLOSE
LM Tunnel Vent valve to LM/CM dP
Ok, Pre-sleep checks complete.
Okeydokes, And we'll see you in the morning, huh?
What do you mean? It is morning.
Hey, that's right. It's been a long day, huh?
Yeah, it sure was.
Ok, the sleeping period starts, let us get into our sleeping bags. [Remove the seats if you have not done yet and don the sleeping bags.]
[This completes the mission, continue the journey in the next chapter]

Title: MISSION 5 - COASTING
Description: The LM has been extracted from the SIVB, and the LM/CSM spacecraft is on its way to the Moon. The next phase will be the beginning of a long coasting period as the spacecraft flies from Earth to the Moon.
BriefingText:
Primary objectives:
 to perform selenological inspection, survey, and sampling of
materials in a preselected region of the Fra Mauro formation;
 to deploy and activate an Apollo lunar surface experiments package;
 to further develop human capability to work in the lunar environment; and
 to obtain photographs of candidate exploration sites.

 ADD COASTING PLAN FOR THE MISSION HERE, UNTIL MCC-2
